    "freetext": "limited research exists about the unique experiences and possible marginalization of children with sexual minority parents. from a larger longitudinal project of diverse adoptive families, we examined cross-sectional data using mixed methods from interviews with 49 adopted children (m age = 8 years; 47\\% female) in 27 two-father and 22 two-mother families. using thematic analysis, we coded themes of awareness of difference, microaggressions, and resilience (i.e., coping and positive family conceptualizations). children experienced \\dqfeeling different\\dq and microaggressions from peers, but generally at a low to medium intensity and with neutral (not negative) emotion. more instances of resilience and positive family conceptualizations were reported than microaggressions or feelings of difference, suggesting that children develop positive perceptions of their family and navigate experiences of difference with resilience. filling important gaps in the literature, we discuss implications of our results for practice and policy. farr, rachel h. and crain, emily e. and oakley, m. k. and cashen, krystal k. and garber, karin j. 2016 microaggressions, feelings of difference, and resilience among adopted children with sexual minority parents aggression;eltern;kinder;lesbisch // lesbian;resilienz // resilience;schwul // gay;sexuelle minderheit // sexual minority 85-104 45 1 0047-2891 journal of youth and adolescence 10.1007/s10964-015-0353-6 article    farr, r., e. crain, m. oakley, k. cashen, and k. garber r. farr, e. crain, m. oakley, k. cashen, k. garber farr, r. et al. farr et al. farr et al."
